| diameter    = {{convert|108.77|km}}
| depth       = 1.8<ref name="crater">{{cite journal | url=https://www.mtholyoke.edu/courses/mdyar/theses/Jared%20Howenstine%20thesis.pdf | title=ANALYSIS OF THE DEPTH-DIAMETER RELATIONSHIP OF MARTIAN CRATERS | author=Jared Howenstine | journal=A Capstone Experience Thesis | date=May 2006}}</ref>
| year        = 
| discoverer  = 
| eponym      = [[Louis Agassiz]]
}}
'''Agassiz''' is an [[impact crater]] on [[Mars]], named in honor of geologist [[Louis Agassiz]](1807–1873). The crater is {{convert|108.77|km}} in diameter<ref name="crater"/> and is located at 271.1°E 69.8°N. The name was approved in 1973 by the [[International Astronomical Union]] (IAU) Working Group for Planetary System Nomenclature (WGPSN).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/81;jsessionid=07A50C2BD95D2C60DC25C430F81B31B8 |title=Planetary Names: Crater, craters: Agassiz on Mars |publisher=Planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov |date= |accessdate=2015-08-18}}</ref>

Nearly a crater diameter to the east is the large [[Schmidt (Martian crater)|Schmidt]] and somewhat 50 km west (half a crater diameter) is [[Heaviside (Martian crater)|Heaviside]], also further northwest in the [[Thaumasia quadrangle]] is the crater [[Bianchini (Martian crater)|Bianchini]]. North is [[Argentea Planum]] (Argentean Plain) and south is [[Parva Planum]].

==See also==
*[[Promontorium Agassiz]] - a promontory on the Moon

