'''Permanent cells''' are [[Cell (biology)|cell]]s that are incapable of [[Cell cycle|regeneration]]. These cells are considered to be terminally differentiated and non proliferative in postnatal life. This includes brain cells, neurons, heart cells, skeletal muscle cells,<ref name=D>{{cite journal|last=Schumacher |first=D|title=Generation of a permanent cell line that supports efficient growth of Marek's disease virus (MDV) by constitutive expression of MDV glycoprotein E.|journal=Junior Genetic Virology|volume=83|issue=8|date=2002|pages=1987-1992|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-83-8-1987|pmid=12124462}}</ref> and [[red blood cells]].<ref>http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/452210/permanent-cell</ref>[[File:Culture of rat brain cells stained with antibody to MAP2 (green), Neurofilament (red) and DNA (blue).jpg|thumbnail|right|Culture of rat brain cells stained with antibody to MAP2 (green), Neurofilament NF-H (red) and DNA (blue). MAP2 is found in neuronal dendrites, while the neurofilament is found predominantly in axons. Antibodies and image courtesy of EnCor Biotechnology]] Disease and virology studies can use permanent cells to maintain cell count and accurately quantify the effects of vaccines.<ref name=D /> Some embryology studies also use permanent cells to avoid harvesting [[Embryonic stem cell|embryonic cells]] from pregnant animals; since the cells are permanent, they may be harvested at a later age when an animal is fully developed.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The validated embryonic stem cell test to predict embryotoxicity in vitro.|last1=Seiler |first1=AE|last2=Spielmann |first2=H|journal=Nature Protocols|volume=6|issue=7|pages=961-978|date=16 June 2011|doi=10.1038/nprot.2011.348|pmid=21720311}}</ref>

